1
00:01:59,600 --> 00:02:01,511
Stop it. Stop it. Stop it.

2
00:02:01,560 --> 00:02:04,233
Let go! Let go! Stop!

3
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:06,716
Damn. Richard Ellespeare died.

4
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:10,679
- He was a professor of mine at Harvard.
- No!

5
00:02:10,760 --> 00:02:13,911
- He was a novelist, humanitarian.
- Hey, hey, back there.

6
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:17,197
- Published eight novels, including the best seller...
- Stop it! Quit it!

7
00:02:17,280 --> 00:02:19,430
Hope's Way, for which
he won the Pulitzer Prize.

8
00:02:19,480 --> 00:02:24,554
- What kind of man was this?
- A man who pursues excellence and nothing less.

9
00:02:24,640 --> 00:02:26,312
- Dad?
- Yes?

10
00:02:26,400 --> 00:02:28,755
I have to go to the bathroom.

11
00:02:30,280 --> 00:02:33,078
Can't you hold it
till we get there?

12
00:02:33,160 --> 00:02:36,038
Mmm, yes. I guess...

13
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:38,310
I can practice
mind over matter.

14
00:02:38,360 --> 00:02:41,432
Atta girl.

15
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:46,479
Oh, look at
the baby cows, Ellie!

16
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:50,189
Oh, my God!
Look at them.

17
00:02:50,280 --> 00:02:53,272
I'm reading, Mom.
And baby cows are calves.

18
00:02:53,360 --> 00:02:56,238
I was never close
to my mother growing up.

19
00:02:59,200 --> 00:03:02,476
Is that something Mr. Best
is going to use against me?

20
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:06,468
Ellen, the D.A.'s not going
to use anything against you.

21
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:09,791
Okay. Because...
Well, I-I agreed to do this because...

22
00:03:09,840 --> 00:03:12,877
Mrs. Best, his wife,
was a friend of my mother's.

23
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:16,311
Do I need an attorney?

24
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:19,119
Nobody in this office
is accusing you of anything.

25
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:24,077
We're well aware that
this kind of thing happens...

26
00:03:24,120 --> 00:03:27,237
all the time
with terminal patients.

27
00:03:27,280 --> 00:03:29,840
It's... It's a small town.
People talk.

28
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:32,155
The D.A. Wants to be able to say
that he looked into it...

29
00:03:32,240 --> 00:03:34,959
and he can put it to bed.

30
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:37,918
What can I say?
It's an election year.

31
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,037
Anyway, were you aware that an autopsy
was being performed on your mother's body?

32
00:03:41,120 --> 00:03:45,352
Yes, uh-huh, at her request.

33
00:03:45,440 --> 00:03:48,876
Uh, actually to find out
the source of the disease.

34
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:51,115
Primarily for my benefit.

35
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:54,789
Mm-hmm.
Where are you living now?

36
00:03:54,840 --> 00:03:59,277
In New York. I've been there
since I finished Harvard.

37
00:04:15,240 --> 00:04:17,071
This living in the suburbs
is going to kill me.

38
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:20,197
Hey, Tweedy, the Bearstone Ladies
predict a stock market crash next month.

39
00:04:20,240 --> 00:04:22,879
- Finish the captions on the junk shot, Casey.
- They're antiques.

40
00:04:22,960 --> 00:04:24,837
- I've got a 110 pulse. I've got to check this again.
- Tweedy.

41
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,996
This story is too good.

42
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:30,038
Senator Sullivan, youngest guy
ever to be elected to the Senate.

43
00:04:30,120 --> 00:04:32,953
His father was a drug dealer,
he overcomes that... excuse me...

44
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:35,600
is on his way to big things,
possibly the presidency...

45
00:04:35,680 --> 00:04:39,275
- until he crashes his car into a tree, kills everyone inside...
- That was actually final draft?

46
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:41,191
While he's on cocaine.

47
00:04:41,280 --> 00:04:43,111
I mean, this is not just good.
This is great.

48
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:45,714
Shakespearean. Sins of the father
revisited on the son...

49
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:47,631
- etcetera, etcetera.
- We've got no interview. He's not talking.

50
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:49,551
- I can get him to talk. I promise you.
- He's checking into rehab.

51
00:04:49,640 --> 00:04:51,551
Some people in town
are describing you as...

52
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:54,160
cold and insensitive.

53
00:04:54,240 --> 00:04:56,913
Um...

54
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,434
Ambition is Ellen Gulden's religion.

55
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:03,911
- She's condescending. She's remote, whatever.
- I can get him to talk.

56
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:06,958
Well, I was ambitious.

57
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:09,230
I still am.

58
00:05:09,320 --> 00:05:12,949
My father taught me to work very hard
at everything I do, and I always have.

59
00:05:13,040 --> 00:05:17,113
I'm not tired.

60
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:21,193
- So you were living a pretty
normal life in New York? - Uh-huh.

61
00:05:21,280 --> 00:05:23,111
- Apartment?
- Uh-huh.

62
00:05:23,200 --> 00:05:26,158
- Roommate?
- No. No roommate.

63
00:05:26,240 --> 00:05:28,071
- Boyfriend?
- Boyfriend.

64
00:05:30,160 --> 00:05:32,549
- Honey, please let me explain.
- Jordan, just get out of here.

65
00:05:32,640 --> 00:05:34,471
- I don't want to see you anymore.
- Come on. I got...

66
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:36,391
I'm standing out here. I got wine,
candles. I got the whole kit.

67
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:38,710
Just go away, Jordan.

68
00:05:38,800 --> 00:05:40,870
EI, can I just talk to you for five
minutes, please? I'll explain everything.

69
00:05:40,920 --> 00:05:42,797
- Go away!
- We were together...

70
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:44,717
since senior year in college.

71
00:05:44,760 --> 00:05:47,194
This one was the last time, okay?

72
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:50,716
Well, not together.
We, uh... We took breaks.

73
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:52,756
You know, a lot of breaks.

74
00:05:54,320 --> 00:05:56,709
That's mean. That's not funny.

75
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:59,951
- He just needed some space.
- Space named Linda.

76
00:06:00,040 --> 00:06:02,315
I'm sorry. Was that her name?
Lori? I don't remember.

77
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:04,396
- Oh, you're so mean.
- Is that not her name?

78
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:07,278
- That... You're so mean.
- Don't get me wrong.

79
00:06:07,320 --> 00:06:09,675
I like him.

80
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,549
Of course, it was, um,
Jules, my best girlfriend...

81
00:06:16,640 --> 00:06:20,952
who, uh, came home with me
to celebrate my father's birthday.

82
00:06:21,040 --> 00:06:24,237
Jordan, um, as usual,
had something he had to do.

83
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:27,028
Oh, this ought to be good.

84
00:06:27,120 --> 00:06:28,997
"Come as your favorite literary
character." I don't know why...

85
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:31,998
my mom can't just throw
a normal birthday party.

86
00:06:32,080 --> 00:06:34,071
Ellie, it's going to be perfectly fine.

87
00:06:38,080 --> 00:06:40,833
Thank you. Thanks.

88
00:06:40,880 --> 00:06:43,519
- Hey!
- Whoo-hoo!

89
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:45,352
- Hi.
- Hi.

90
00:06:45,440 --> 00:06:48,079
- Oh, good hat. Uh-huh. - Really
good hat. Really good everything.

91
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:49,997
Thanks. What'd you guys
come dressed as?

92
00:06:50,080 --> 00:06:52,071
The Sylvia Plath twins?

93
00:06:52,120 --> 00:06:54,236
- Brian, you know I can't do costumes.
- Why?

94
00:06:54,320 --> 00:06:56,834
- It's just so... Mom.
- Human?

95
00:06:56,880 --> 00:06:59,155
- So what have you guys been up to?
- God!

96
00:06:59,240 --> 00:07:01,196
- Ooh. Mm-hmm.
- It's writing and deadlines.

97
00:07:01,240 --> 00:07:03,117
Take me away.

98
00:07:03,160 --> 00:07:05,037
- Okay.
- Oh, wait!

99
00:07:05,080 --> 00:07:07,753
Somebody just finished summer school,
didn't he? Congratulations!

100
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:10,360
- Actually, I didn't finish.
- That's great!

101
00:07:10,440 --> 00:07:12,908
What?

102
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:15,468
I, Brian Gulden...

103
00:07:15,560 --> 00:07:20,076
son of Mr. American Literature and the
romantics, failed American Literature.

104
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:23,831
You're serious?

105
00:07:23,920 --> 00:07:27,913
- Yeah.
- Well, way to go.

106
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,959
- How did you do that?
- I blew the test, Ellen.

107
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:35,111
Brian.

108
00:07:36,600 --> 00:07:38,750
Did you tell Dad?

109
00:07:38,800 --> 00:07:40,791
No.

110
00:07:40,880 --> 00:07:44,509
Just 'cause I'm failing
doesn't make me a moron.

111
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:46,471
Yoo-hoo! Hi!

112
00:07:46,560 --> 00:07:48,437
- There she is.
- Hi, Mom.

113
00:07:48,520 --> 00:07:50,636
Your dad's not here.
The coast is clear. Gimme! Gimme!

114
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:52,870
Gimme!
Hi, Jules.

115
00:07:52,960 --> 00:07:55,315
Hi.

116
00:07:55,400 --> 00:07:57,709
- Hi. You too.
- Good to see you.

117
00:07:57,800 --> 00:07:59,631
- Let me get your...
- Oh, no, no, no. I got it.

118
00:07:59,720 --> 00:08:01,676
- Are you sure? Okay.
- Yeah, yeah. Thanks. Oh, thank you.

119
00:08:02,800 --> 00:08:05,678
- Wow.
- Thank you.

120
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:09,036
You got a cab? I would have sent
Brian to come and pick you up.

121
00:08:09,080 --> 00:08:10,991
- You should have told me.
- Oh, that's okay.

122
00:08:11,080 --> 00:08:12,911
Come in. Come in,
come in, come in.

123
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,117
- God, this must have taken you days.
- Oh, well, yes.

124
00:08:16,200 --> 00:08:18,031
- Jules, you look wonderful.
- Oh, thanks.

125
00:08:18,120 --> 00:08:21,032
- I just cut my hair.
- Oh. It looks gorgeous.

126
00:08:21,120 --> 00:08:23,680
- And your hair looks great too.
- Oh, thank you.

127
00:08:23,760 --> 00:08:26,877
Oh, this... It's yarn.
Look. Guess who I am.

128
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:28,791
Hmm? Oh!

129
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:32,555
Oh, wait! Clue.

130
00:08:32,600 --> 00:08:35,910
- Oh... If I only had a brain
- A heart

131
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:38,309
A brain
and whatever else

132
00:08:38,400 --> 00:08:40,994
Oh, well.
You're right, as usual.

133
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:45,636
- So, let me see. Who are you?
- Uh...

134
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:50,276
- Don't tell me. Let me guess. - Actually,
you know what? We-We kind of forgot.

135
00:08:50,320 --> 00:08:52,550
But is was only because
we were trying to hurry...

136
00:08:52,600 --> 00:08:56,513
'cause, of course, we wanted
to be here on time, so...

137
00:08:56,560 --> 00:08:58,790
- God, that cake looks so good. So, we're just us.
- Oh.

138
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:02,230
That's okay.
That's okay, Ellie. That's...

139
00:09:02,320 --> 00:09:04,390
Ooh!
But I have an idea.

140
00:09:04,480 --> 00:09:07,597
I do have a Thanksgiving
costume upstairs.

141
00:09:07,680 --> 00:09:09,830
- That's okay.
- I could whip something up for you. It's a turkey!

142
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:12,070
- No, really. It's okay. It's all right.
- It's really...

143
00:09:12,160 --> 00:09:14,276
- Can I help you with anything?
- Oh, yes, thanks.

144
00:09:14,320 --> 00:09:18,359
- You could take those dishes, put them in the buffet. Umm...
- Sure.

145
00:09:18,440 --> 00:09:21,193
And Ellie... Ellie?

146
00:09:21,240 --> 00:09:25,677
You can... keep-keep, uh,
slicing the bread...

147
00:09:25,760 --> 00:09:28,593
- with this knife, okay?
- Thank you.

148
00:09:28,680 --> 00:09:31,956
I read your piece
on Geraldine Ferraro.

149
00:09:32,040 --> 00:09:33,871
My brilliant daughter.

150
00:09:33,960 --> 00:09:36,758
I was so... proud of you.

151
00:09:36,840 --> 00:09:39,559
It's no big deal.
It's just a little follow-up piece.

152
00:09:39,600 --> 00:09:41,955
Back and forth.
Saw on it.

153
00:09:43,400 --> 00:09:45,391
- Do you think that Dad read it?
- Oh, I'm sure he did.

154
00:09:45,480 --> 00:09:49,519
You know your dad.
But he doesn't talk shop with me.

155
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:53,189
Fuck.

156
00:09:53,240 --> 00:09:55,549
Nope. It's okay. It's okay.
It's not even bleeding.

157
00:09:55,600 --> 00:09:57,511
- It's fine. It's really fine.
- Wrap it up.

158
00:09:57,600 --> 00:10:00,114
- Okay. Thank you.
- Brown paper. There's something in it that stops the bleeding.

159
00:10:00,200 --> 00:10:03,317
- Did you know that? -
Really? - Okay, thanks.

160
00:10:03,400 --> 00:10:06,472
- Oh! Oh, dear.
- Sorry.

161
00:10:06,520 --> 00:10:09,080
- No, I'll get it.
- That's all right. Don't throw the pieces out...

162
00:10:09,160 --> 00:10:11,549
- because I'm going to use it in my mosaic table I'm making.
- Don't worry.

163
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:14,831
- We got it.
- Keep your finger up and wrapped in the bag.

164
00:10:14,920 --> 00:10:17,832
Hello?
There's no place like home.

165
00:10:17,920 --> 00:10:20,195
- Thank God.
- Are we the first ones here?

166
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:23,632
- Ellen! Oh, it's good to see you.
- Oh, yeah.

167
00:10:23,720 --> 00:10:25,551
- You're lookin' tired.
- Ellen.

168
00:10:25,640 --> 00:10:29,679
- Now, who are you supposed to be? Who?
- Oh, I'm Lizzie Borden.

169
00:10:29,720 --> 00:10:32,029
You know, Lizzie Borden:
"Took an axe...

170
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:35,277
gave her mother 40 whacks."

171
00:10:35,320 --> 00:10:37,709
Oh, Mrs. Best, can you
hold the door? Oh, thanks.

172
00:10:37,800 --> 00:10:40,519
- Help! Ellen, I just saw Dad. He just turned the corner.
- Oh! Hey!

173
00:10:40,560 --> 00:10:42,596
Jules! Jules!
Come help. Come help.

174
00:10:42,640 --> 00:10:45,200
Okay.

175
00:10:45,280 --> 00:10:48,477
- So, um, Snow White, explain. What was that?
- Oh.

176
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:53,031
Mrs. Best, the D.A.'s wife,
she's in my mom's cult.

177
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:54,957
The Minnies, yeah.

178
00:10:55,000 --> 00:10:56,877
They're named after
some local do-gooder...

179
00:10:56,920 --> 00:10:59,912
who used to decorate Christmas trees
in the town square.

180
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:02,468
- And, um, they're a cult?
- Woman's group.

181
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:05,233
- Right. Right.
- You know, bake sales, tag sales, all of that.

182
00:11:05,320 --> 00:11:07,151
- Come on. You be nice.
- Do-good stuff.

183
00:11:07,240 --> 00:11:09,071
- No. Hi.
- You must be Ellen. I'm Harold Simpkey.

184
00:11:09,160 --> 00:11:10,991
- I teach music over...
- Harold, could you, um...

185
00:11:11,080 --> 00:11:13,753
He's here!
Hurry up! Hurry up!

186
00:11:13,840 --> 00:11:15,956
Hurry up! Here he is.

187
00:11:16,040 --> 00:11:17,871
Everybody, get-get-get down!

188
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:22,750
Shh! Ralph, move your... Shh!

189
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:30,151
Quiet!

190
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:35,156
Kate?

191
00:11:38,520 --> 00:11:40,397
Kate?

192
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:43,711
- Kate?
- Surprise!

193
00:11:47,240 --> 00:11:49,071
Happy birthday!

194
00:11:52,560 --> 00:11:56,838
No. Look at all of you.

195
00:11:56,880 --> 00:11:58,757
Kate.

196
00:12:01,040 --> 00:12:03,076
How did you pull this off?
Bravo!

197
00:12:03,120 --> 00:12:05,839
Come on, Dad, speech.

198
00:12:05,880 --> 00:12:08,713
Speech! Speech!

199
00:12:13,640 --> 00:12:16,393
I'm quite out of breath with walking
home. It's only in going uphill...

200
00:12:16,440 --> 00:12:19,910
that you realize
you're headed downhill.

201
00:12:24,720 --> 00:12:26,870
Thank you.
Thank you. Thank you all for coming.

202
00:12:26,960 --> 00:12:29,997
I'm really...
I'm really very touched.

203
00:12:30,040 --> 00:12:32,429
I'm very touched.

204
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:39,432
So, I guess this is the...

205
00:12:39,480 --> 00:12:42,119
last class of the semester.

206
00:12:43,880 --> 00:12:47,077
Thank you for taking this journey
with me. It's been a lot of fun.

207
00:12:47,120 --> 00:12:51,432
And have a great summer.

208
00:13:16,560 --> 00:13:18,630
There it is.

209
00:13:18,720 --> 00:13:21,075
The National Book Award.

210
00:13:23,600 --> 00:13:28,230
Oh, wow. He knows Oliver Most.

211
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:30,510
Yeah, they went to Harvard together.

212
00:13:30,600 --> 00:13:32,556
Come see this. Come here.

213
00:13:34,080 --> 00:13:36,878
It's his novel, Comeback Inn.

214
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:39,315
He's been working on it for years.

215
00:13:40,960 --> 00:13:44,396
Took Milton ten
to finish my favorite poem.

216
00:13:44,440 --> 00:13:47,273
Oh, here's his collected essays.

217
00:13:47,320 --> 00:13:49,231
I read this first chapter.

218
00:13:49,320 --> 00:13:51,151
- Yeah?
- Uh-huh.

219
00:13:51,240 --> 00:13:54,391
And?

220
00:13:54,480 --> 00:13:56,869
- It's great.
- Uh-huh.

221
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:03,997
So, uh, what-what'd he say
about your article?

222
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,036
Oh, I don't believe it.

223
00:14:10,120 --> 00:14:12,554
You didn't ask him, did you?

224
00:14:13,560 --> 00:14:15,437
Ellie. Tsk.

225
00:14:15,920 --> 00:14:18,354
- That's what they called me.
- Did they now?

226
00:14:18,440 --> 00:14:20,271
You know,
having the dubious distinction...

227
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:23,750
of having been called "Big Al"
when you were this diminutive...

228
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:27,719
package is a challenge
to confidence...

229
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:30,115
but you have obviously
survived it, have you not?

230
00:14:30,160 --> 00:14:33,709
- Yes.
- So here you have in front of you a living example...

231
00:14:33,800 --> 00:14:36,872
of-of everything
you're trying to achieve.

232
00:14:36,960 --> 00:14:39,633
I would just say get an ice breaker
and break out of it.

233
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:41,551
- I'm havin' a lot of trouble.
- Listen...

234
00:14:41,640 --> 00:14:45,394
a writer calls his friend, he says,
"I've just finished writing a story.

235
00:14:45,480 --> 00:14:47,789
"It's not very good.
In fact, it's terrible.

236
00:14:47,880 --> 00:14:50,314
The worst part of it is
it's the best I can do."

237
00:14:50,360 --> 00:14:55,753
The writer is John Steinbeck.
The book is Grapes of Wrath!

238
00:14:56,560 --> 00:14:59,950
- Hi! Hi.
- Hey! Hi.

239
00:15:02,160 --> 00:15:04,833
- Happy birthday.
- Thank you.

240
00:15:04,880 --> 00:15:07,599
I'm afraid with 55
staring at me in the face...

241
00:15:07,640 --> 00:15:09,835
I'm developing inflammation
of the sentence structure...

242
00:15:09,880 --> 00:15:13,350
and a definite hardening
of the paragraphs, but...

243
00:15:13,440 --> 00:15:16,989
- How are you?
- Oh, no. How are you?

244
00:15:17,040 --> 00:15:19,429
You knew all about
this little thing, didn't you?

245
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:21,710
- Huh?
- No, actually, I didn't.

246
00:15:21,800 --> 00:15:23,597
Hmm.

247
00:15:25,080 --> 00:15:28,197
Well, did you get a chance
to look at my latest piece?

248
00:15:28,240 --> 00:15:31,710
Yes. Yes, of course.

249
00:15:31,760 --> 00:15:34,593
The Minnies seem to get
their literature from Disney.

250
00:15:34,640 --> 00:15:37,200
I know.

251
00:15:37,240 --> 00:15:39,117
- Hey!
- Oh, my God, they're everywhere.

252
00:15:39,160 --> 00:15:43,790
Enemy forces at 2:00.
Danger, Will Robertson. Danger.

253
00:15:43,880 --> 00:15:47,156
- It's Robinson. Robinson.
- Oh, Robinson.

254
00:15:47,240 --> 00:15:50,312
Safe.

255
00:15:50,360 --> 00:15:52,237
Safe for the moment.

256
00:15:55,200 --> 00:15:57,509
That was better. That was better.
Now I'll show you...

257
00:15:57,600 --> 00:15:59,431
About your article...

258
00:15:59,520 --> 00:16:01,476
- Hmm.
- I don't want to interfere, you know.

259
00:16:01,520 --> 00:16:04,239
- You are doing just fine.
- Oh, no. Come on.

260
00:16:04,280 --> 00:16:07,272
Come on. You know your criticism,
it helps me so much.

261
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:09,197
I really appreciate it.

262
00:16:11,560 --> 00:16:13,391
All right.

263
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:15,311
Writer to writer.

264
00:16:18,680 --> 00:16:22,150
- Less is more.
- Hmm.

265
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:26,512
Your approach is a little
overemotional at times.

266
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:30,309
It needs to be more succinct. The word
choice needs to be more muscular.

267
00:16:30,360 --> 00:16:33,193
Ellen, you've got a great talent,
but it's not enough.

268
00:16:33,280 --> 00:16:35,111
You have to reach, goddamn it.

269
00:16:35,200 --> 00:16:37,191
When I was 20 years old
working at the New Yorker...

270
00:16:37,240 --> 00:16:39,595
I would spend a whole day
working on one sentence.

271
00:16:39,640 --> 00:16:42,518
I mean, Lord knows I could...

272
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:49,268
Wait a minute.
It's your best work to date. It's...

273
00:16:51,600 --> 00:16:56,310
It's not your fault. It's like
the problem is that editor, damn it.

274
00:16:56,400 --> 00:16:59,472
- What is his name? Uh, Tw... Twimpy?
- Tweedy.

275
00:16:59,560 --> 00:17:01,391
Yeah.

276
00:17:01,480 --> 00:17:03,675
- George? Well, see ya.
- He's a fool as far as...

277
00:17:03,760 --> 00:17:05,591
- Hey.
- Yeah? We're hiding.

278
00:17:05,680 --> 00:17:09,389
I know. Come inside. It's time to
blow out the candles and make a wish!

279
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:11,994
Oh, I wish we were... alone.

280
00:17:12,080 --> 00:17:15,436
Well, we're not yet. So hurry up.
Come on. Everybody's waiting.

281
00:17:21,160 --> 00:17:22,991
Man, that's solid.

282
00:17:23,080 --> 00:17:25,958
Brian, how's Harvard treating ya?

283
00:17:27,320 --> 00:17:29,390
Can't complain.
We beat Oxford in the Prentice Cup.

284
00:17:30,640 --> 00:17:33,837
I was referring
to your courses.

285
00:17:33,920 --> 00:17:35,956
Summer school was all right?

286
00:17:36,040 --> 00:17:38,429
Uh, fine.

287
00:17:38,480 --> 00:17:41,870
Yeah? You didn't have
any more problems, did ya?

288
00:17:41,960 --> 00:17:43,791
Nope.
Everything's fine, Dad.

289
00:17:43,880 --> 00:17:46,030
I'd be glad to help
by talking to your professors.

290
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:49,237
- I'd be glad to look at your...
- I said everything's fine.

291
00:17:51,520 --> 00:17:53,795
Well, good.

292
00:17:56,040 --> 00:17:57,871
Good.

293
00:18:04,240 --> 00:18:08,074
- He's had a few, huh?
- It's his birthday.

294
00:18:08,480 --> 00:18:10,471
Good night!
Good night, Mary!

295
00:18:10,560 --> 00:18:12,471
- Good night, guys.
- Good night... What's his name?

296
00:18:12,560 --> 00:18:15,597
Hewitt.

297
00:18:17,520 --> 00:18:20,114
Hewitt. That's...

298
00:18:22,120 --> 00:18:24,918
Don't do anything.
I'll do it in the morning, honey.

299
00:18:26,160 --> 00:18:29,948
Well, thank you,
thank you one and all for a...

300
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:31,877
a beautiful birthday.

301
00:18:31,920 --> 00:18:34,957
- Happy birthday.
- Happy birthday, Dad.

302
00:18:35,040 --> 00:18:38,157
Happy birthday, darling.

303
00:18:38,240 --> 00:18:41,312
- Good night. Uh-huh.
- Good night?

304
00:18:41,360 --> 00:18:43,954
You're not going to bed.
You're not going to sleep, anyway.

305
00:18:44,040 --> 00:18:46,998
- Oh, God.
- I have to get up early, you know.

306
00:18:47,080 --> 00:18:48,911
I have Dr. Cohn in the morning.

307
00:18:49,000 --> 00:18:52,754
Shh!

308
00:18:52,840 --> 00:18:55,274
Oh, do you like Bette Midler?

309
00:18:55,320 --> 00:18:58,153
Oh! You.

310
00:18:59,160 --> 00:19:01,993
Come on. Come on.

311
00:19:02,080 --> 00:19:04,071
Just one.

312
00:19:44,160 --> 00:19:45,991
I don't care about that.

313
00:20:12,800 --> 00:20:15,712
I knew my mother was going
to the doctor, but, uh...

314
00:20:15,760 --> 00:20:19,196
I didn't really know
what for.

315
00:20:20,680 --> 00:20:22,511
So you didn't ask.

316
00:20:24,400 --> 00:20:26,789
No.

317
00:20:26,880 --> 00:20:29,348
What poem begins,
"'Twas the night before Christmas"?

318
00:20:29,400 --> 00:20:32,392
Uh, it's not called,
"'Twas the night before Christmas."

319
00:20:32,480 --> 00:20:35,040
It's called, uh... I can recite
the whole thing. Does that count?

320
00:20:35,120 --> 00:20:37,156
Anybody need any coffee?

321
00:20:37,200 --> 00:20:39,760
- We just need the title. No, thank you.
- No? Okay.

322
00:20:39,800 --> 00:20:42,519
- I'm gonna go through the whole thing.
- Don't let him cheat!

323
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:44,875
Please!

324
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:49,830
Oh, my God.
"A Visit from St. Nick."

325
00:20:49,880 --> 00:20:52,872
Oh, man! Don't I get the point?

326
00:20:52,920 --> 00:20:54,797
Hey!

327
00:21:02,280 --> 00:21:05,590
- Where's Mom?
- They're going to keep her overnight.

328
00:21:08,920 --> 00:21:11,434
She's going to have to have surgery.

329
00:21:13,760 --> 00:21:15,591
Surgery?

330
00:21:17,800 --> 00:21:21,952
Yes, they're...
They're going to try to take it out.

331
00:21:24,280 --> 00:21:26,157
It's cancer?

332
00:21:35,840 --> 00:21:39,549
- Are they sure?
- I'm going back out there to spend the night.

333
00:21:42,040 --> 00:21:43,917
Is she going to die?

334
00:21:43,960 --> 00:21:47,794
No, she's not going to die.

335
00:21:47,880 --> 00:21:53,034
After the operation, she may need
radiation or chemotherapy.

336
00:21:53,080 --> 00:21:55,674
The doctor said that
that can be very debilitating...

337
00:21:55,760 --> 00:21:59,116
in which case she would need somebody
to take care of her during the day.

338
00:22:01,120 --> 00:22:02,951
Actually, l...

339
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:07,112
I want you to-to move home...

340
00:22:07,200 --> 00:22:10,272
to take care of her.

341
00:22:10,320 --> 00:22:12,515
Move home?

342
00:22:12,560 --> 00:22:17,031
- Brian is at school.
- Dad, what about my job?

343
00:22:17,120 --> 00:22:20,078
Well, you can
freelance from here.

344
00:22:20,120 --> 00:22:22,953
She's going to need help
during the day.

345
00:22:23,040 --> 00:22:24,917
Well...

346
00:22:25,000 --> 00:22:27,434
Maybe you could take sabbatical.
I mean, it's been four years since...

347
00:22:27,520 --> 00:22:29,715
- you took one for the novel.
- A sabbatical is out of the question.

348
00:22:29,800 --> 00:22:32,758
I have a department to run,
and I have to make a living.

349
00:22:32,840 --> 00:22:35,957
As you well know, the advance
on my novel was spent years ago...

350
00:22:36,040 --> 00:22:37,871
on yours and Brian's education.

351
00:22:37,960 --> 00:22:42,954
Dad, I have to do my interviews
and my research in New York.

352
00:22:43,040 --> 00:22:45,508
You know my job.
I cannot just drop everything.

353
00:22:45,560 --> 00:22:48,632
I may never catch up again.
It could ruin my career.

354
00:22:48,720 --> 00:22:51,075
- We can get a nurse and I will come home every weekend.
- A nurse?

355
00:22:51,120 --> 00:22:54,908
We're not getting a nurse. Your mother
didn't get a nurse when you had chicken pox.

356
00:22:54,960 --> 00:22:58,794
A nurse. You know she won't tolerate
having strangers in this house.

357
00:22:58,840 --> 00:23:02,310
- But, Dad...
- Your mother needs you, Ellen. Jesus Christ!

358
00:23:02,400 --> 00:23:05,198
You've got a Harvard education,
but where is your heart?

359
00:23:12,200 --> 00:23:14,031
Excuse me.

360
00:23:19,720 --> 00:23:21,756
- Honey? Hi.
- Hey.

361
00:23:21,840 --> 00:23:25,549
- So sorry I'm late. Sorry. Hey, Jules.
- Hi. Bye.

362
00:23:25,640 --> 00:23:28,552
- Okay. Hi. Mmm, kiss.
- Hi.

363
00:23:31,040 --> 00:23:32,871
You okay?

364
00:23:32,960 --> 00:23:34,951
Here, give me your bag.

365
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:38,310
- What's the matter? She's what?
- My mom is sick.

366
00:23:40,120 --> 00:23:42,076
Ellen, a sick mother means
three weeks off...

367
00:23:42,160 --> 00:23:44,310
and a very nice arrangement
of flowers sent by the staff.

368
00:23:44,400 --> 00:23:46,960
Yeah, still holding.
You're doing great here.

369
00:23:47,040 --> 00:23:49,110
If you leave there's no guarantee. All
I could offer you is some freelance work.

370
00:23:49,200 --> 00:23:53,830
Okay, but I'm still going to finish
the Sullivan piece from home.

371
00:23:53,880 --> 00:23:57,395
How are you going to do that?

372
00:23:57,480 --> 00:24:00,597
- Actually, Casey said that he has a way into Sullivan too.
- No.

373
00:24:00,680 --> 00:24:03,592
This is my piece.
I can do it.

374
00:24:03,640 --> 00:24:05,676
Okay. I know what this is about.

375
00:24:05,760 --> 00:24:07,591
You want an upgrade.

376
00:24:07,680 --> 00:24:09,989
Well, you got it.
I don't know what it is yet...

377
00:24:10,080 --> 00:24:12,036
but it's yours.

378
00:24:14,520 --> 00:24:16,715
You really think that
someone would come in here...

379
00:24:16,800 --> 00:24:19,917
and say that their mother
has cancer for a promotion?

380
00:24:21,320 --> 00:24:23,151
Ellen, this is New York.

381
00:24:39,960 --> 00:24:41,837
Ellen Gulden.

382
00:24:41,880 --> 00:24:43,871
Hello, sweetheart. It's Dad.

383
00:24:43,920 --> 00:24:45,797
Hi, Dad.

384
00:24:45,840 --> 00:24:49,515
- You okay?
- Yeah, I'm fine.

385
00:24:49,600 --> 00:24:54,435
- Listen, I'm really sorry.
- I'm sorry too.

386
00:24:55,040 --> 00:24:57,315
Don't forget
to make an extra set of keys...

387
00:24:57,360 --> 00:24:59,749
- in case you need to get in.
- I know. I know. You know what I need to do?

388
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:01,677
- I've got to disconnect the phone.
- Yes, by Wednesday.

389
00:25:01,720 --> 00:25:03,597
- By Wednesday.
- Okay. I'll call then.

390
00:25:03,640 --> 00:25:06,473
- When is she moving in? Saturday?
- Thursday.

391
00:25:06,520 --> 00:25:09,398
- Okay. What are you gonna do?
- Call you when I get there.

392
00:25:09,480 --> 00:25:13,029
- You always forget, then I worry.
- I won't forget. I promise.

393
00:25:15,120 --> 00:25:17,350
Thanks. Okay.

394
00:25:19,320 --> 00:25:21,834
Sweetie, I'm all nervous.

395
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:24,957
I've never asked anybody
to live with me.

396
00:25:25,040 --> 00:25:27,429
- I'm gonna miss you.
- I'm gonna miss you too.

397
00:26:28,240 --> 00:26:30,117
Ellie?

398
00:26:30,160 --> 00:26:32,469
- You're home!
- Mm-hmm.

399
00:26:34,520 --> 00:26:38,991
I was just... I was remembering when
I moved these plates from Princeton.

400
00:26:39,080 --> 00:26:43,119
- Oh, yeah.
- Remember? And Brian was practicing juggling.

401
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:45,151
- So, how are you?
- I'm fine. I'm fine.

402
00:26:45,200 --> 00:26:47,077
- Good.
- I just have to take it easy.

403
00:26:47,120 --> 00:26:49,350
My oncologist, who is...
you'll love this...

404
00:26:49,400 --> 00:26:52,312
a woman,
says no upholstering...

405
00:26:52,400 --> 00:26:54,675
no furniture refinishing.

406
00:26:54,760 --> 00:26:57,035
Oh, no. What are you gonna do?

407
00:26:57,120 --> 00:27:00,237
Can you stay
the whole weekend?

408
00:27:00,280 --> 00:27:05,752
Uh, didn't Dad...
Oh, he didn't...

409
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:09,674
Well, um,
I'm home for a while.

410
00:27:09,760 --> 00:27:12,274
I took some time off from work.

411
00:27:12,360 --> 00:27:16,069
Home where? Here?
Well, what about your job...

412
00:27:16,160 --> 00:27:17,991
and your little apartment
and everything?

413
00:27:18,080 --> 00:27:20,389
Well, I'm gonna work
from here, so...

414
00:27:20,480 --> 00:27:22,436
- Oh, don't worry about it.
- Oh, no.

415
00:27:22,480 --> 00:27:24,357
- Tweedy said that it's fine.
- Oh, no, no, no.

416
00:27:24,400 --> 00:27:26,277
Not to play nursemaid to me.

417
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:28,595
- Oh, no. That's not...
- Oh, I don't need...

418
00:27:28,680 --> 00:27:31,148
Man, you'll hate me.
I'll just make you some dinner.

419
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:33,071
No, I want to stay.

420
00:27:33,160 --> 00:27:35,310
At least until you feel better.

421
00:27:35,400 --> 00:27:37,960
I mean, it's the right thing.

422
00:27:39,680 --> 00:27:41,796
For who?

423
00:27:41,840 --> 00:27:43,876
- Whose idea was this?
- Mine.

424
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:47,431
Dad, and...
Well, it was both of ours.

425
00:27:47,520 --> 00:27:51,399
He shouldn't have asked you to do this,
honey, because he knows you.

426
00:27:51,440 --> 00:27:54,432
- He knows this will never work.
- No. Now, I told Dad...

427
00:27:54,480 --> 00:27:56,789
that I want to do this
and I'm going to.

428
00:27:56,880 --> 00:27:58,950
So, that's final.
Okay?

429
00:28:01,960 --> 00:28:05,191
Okay. Okay.

430
00:28:06,320 --> 00:28:09,471
Okay. Oh, my girl.

431
00:28:09,520 --> 00:28:12,910
I'm gonna make you
some cinnamon toast.

432
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:15,389
And I'll get you
a cup of tea too.

433
00:28:15,440 --> 00:28:17,317
Okay.

434
00:28:30,320 --> 00:28:34,029
I'm glad you're home. Thanks.

435
00:28:34,120 --> 00:28:36,031
She didn't know I was coming.

436
00:28:36,080 --> 00:28:38,594
Well, you know how
your mother is.

437
00:28:38,640 --> 00:28:40,517
If she'd known...

438
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:42,790
she probably would've redecorated
your entire bedroom.

439
00:28:44,840 --> 00:28:47,115
What's that smell?

440
00:28:47,200 --> 00:28:50,670
Um, that is
an old writer's trick.

441
00:28:52,880 --> 00:28:55,440
Schiller believed that
his body sabotaged...

442
00:28:55,480 --> 00:28:57,869
the attention of his mind
while he was writing.

443
00:28:57,960 --> 00:28:59,791
So, he engaged his body...

444
00:28:59,880 --> 00:29:03,919
with a simple stimulant, apples...

445
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:05,911
to free his mind.

446
00:29:06,000 --> 00:29:09,959
So far, all it's done for me is
make me hungry for apple pie á la mode.

447
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:13,191
So, what have you been
working on recently?

448
00:29:13,240 --> 00:29:15,151
My interview with James Sullivan.

449
00:29:15,240 --> 00:29:18,755
- Senator Sullivan?
- Mm-hmm.

450
00:29:18,800 --> 00:29:21,917
That's impressive.
That's a big story.

451
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:24,992
You know, I've been
meaning to ask you.

452
00:29:25,040 --> 00:29:27,508
Random House has been asking me
who I'd like to write...

453
00:29:27,600 --> 00:29:32,469
the introduction to Volume Two
of my Collected Essays.

454
00:29:32,560 --> 00:29:35,438
It's coming out in the spring.

455
00:29:35,480 --> 00:29:37,357
Feel free to say no,
but if you had the time...

456
00:29:37,400 --> 00:29:39,550
how would you feel
about writing the introduction?

457
00:29:39,600 --> 00:29:43,229
- Are you serious?
- Mm-hmm.

458
00:29:43,280 --> 00:29:48,400
- I would love to.
- Great. Great.

459
00:29:48,440 --> 00:29:53,195
They envision some biographical sketch
or interview perhaps.

460
00:29:53,240 --> 00:29:56,073
- I'll help you write the questions, if you want.
- Okay.

461
00:29:56,120 --> 00:29:58,634
Here's some literary criticism...

462
00:29:58,680 --> 00:30:00,557
in case you haven't
seen any of that recently.

463
00:30:00,600 --> 00:30:03,353
And two, three examples of my work
in case you don't carry that...

464
00:30:03,440 --> 00:30:05,510
around in your bags
with you wherever you go.

465
00:30:05,600 --> 00:30:07,431
And, wait.

466
00:30:11,600 --> 00:30:13,477
Wow.

467
00:30:13,520 --> 00:30:16,796
Could you wash these for me?
No starch.

468
00:30:16,880 --> 00:30:18,711
And this pocket
needs to be stitched.

469
00:30:22,240 --> 00:30:24,071
Thanks for taking care of this.

470
00:30:26,960 --> 00:30:30,919
Ellie!
Tell Dad dinner's on the table.

471
00:30:30,960 --> 00:30:33,838
Sweetie, later on tonight,
I'm gonna run you a vanilla bath.

472
00:30:33,920 --> 00:30:35,831
That'll help you
go to sleep. Okay?

473
00:30:47,600 --> 00:30:50,034
- Morning.
- Good morning.

474
00:30:50,120 --> 00:30:52,236
Good morning
Mary sunshine

475
00:30:52,320 --> 00:30:55,118
Did you wake so soon

476
00:30:55,200 --> 00:30:58,158
- Remember when we used to sing you that?
